  "body": "**ðŸ§ Motivation**\r\n\r\nSome context: I was experimenting with a solidity feature that can tell users if a state variable can be moved to an immutable (thereby saving gas, if the variable is read.) I noticed that `totalSupply` in examples of ERC20 token implementations could actually be converted into an `immutable`. That is because most tokens only mint during the construction, and does not change it during runtime.\r\n\r\n**ðŸ“ Proposal**\r\n\r\nHave an ERC20 (and other relevant token standards) implementation where `totalSupply` is `immutable` and the value has to be set at most once during construction.\r\n\r\n**Comments**\r\n\r\nThe main argument for converting a state variable into an immutable is the gas savings on reading from storage. However, I don't really believe that fixed supply contracts need to read its total supply on chain, making the argument less effective.\r\n\r\nAn argument against the change is code duplication in OpenZeppelin's library implementations.\r\n\r\nSo overall, I don't believe this change is useful. Regardless, I'm opening this issue, to get some feedback on the proposal.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
